. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Existing </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">evidence </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">suggests that, although important</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, it is not </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">only </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">staff qualifications and staffing </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ratios that are the most important factors in determining children’s outcomes. In</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">stead, it is the quality of care and relationships that are central to safeguarding.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">This practice is consistent with government reforms of social work more widely, stemm</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ing from the Munro Review</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.  </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="11" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.68pt; padding-left:1.02pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">It </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">has long been accepted that forging close, trusting relationships is at the heart </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">of effective residential care. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Children need someone that they can trust, someone they turn to, who listens to them and understand</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">s their needs. We know </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">from </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">NSPCC</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> research w</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ith young people</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> who have experience of a variety of foster care and residential care placements</span><a name="_ftnref7"></a><a href="#_ftn7">[7]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">that </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">too often this is not the case.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> Building these relationships requires carers to understand</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> the individual needs of children. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="12" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.68pt; padding-left:1.02pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The NSPCC recently </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">convened a seminar of local authority</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> care home providers, local authorities and academics to examine effective safeguarding practice in residential care. The seminar concluded that of utmost importance were relationships between staff and children, the ne</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">eds assessment of children and the role of commissioners. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Participants agreed that there needs to be more of a focus on</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> staff development which includes leadership, ethos of the home and the ability of staff to listen, understand and empathise with childre</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">n and young people.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Therefore, we believe that the focus on these relationships and how they can be developed and strengthened is currently missing from the proposed reforms. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; text-decoration:underline">Variable standards i</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; text-decoration:underline">n current safeguarding practice</span></p><ol start="13" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.68pt; padding-left:1.02pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Through the high profile child sexual exploitation cases, concerning evidence has emerged that some professionals responsible for safeguarding children in care have demonstrated callous and dismissive attitudes toward young people who have gone missing fro</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">m care and experienced abuse and exploitation. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="14" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.68pt; padding-left:1.02pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The Home Affairs Committee concluded fr</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">om evidence it received that</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> many victims of child sexual exploitation have been failed by people throughout the system. The report commented that professionals needed </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">to change their attitudes towards the word ‘consent’. Young people under the age of 16 cannot give legal consent to sexual relations and therefore it is ‘non-consensual, unlawful and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">wrong. Some</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> young people currently feel very uncared for by the care syst</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">em. This coupled with being placed far away from their family and friends can lead to children feeling unsafe and lonely. Inappropriate professional attitudes and stigmatising behaviour can feed into children’s beliefs that the care system is not concerned</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> with their individual well-being.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="15" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.68pt; padding-left:1.02pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">It is not </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">currently </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">possible to judge to what extent these attitudes and poor standards of care are isolated incidents, or more widespread across the residential care sector. However, they are </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">clearly serious enough to w</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">arrant considered attention to the question of how we can ensure that we achieve high standards of safeguarding and emotionally sensitive care in all residential settings.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; text-decoration:underline">Understanding </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; text-decoration:underline">the views and experience of children</span></p><ol start="16" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.68pt; padding-left:1.02pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">If we are to prevent children from going missing from care, it is essential that we first understand the motivations behind their actions. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">NSPCC’s 2012 report</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> on the views of young people with </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">experience of foster care and residential care placements</span><a name="_ftnref8"></a><a href="#_ftn8">[8]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> show</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ed that many young people ra</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">n away from care because they were frustrated with authority figures who had power over them and did not seem to be able to see things from their point of view. Some young people had been restrained or locked in their room. When</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> they were asked how professionals could prevent missing incidents, participants in the NSPCC’s research also placed a strong emphasis on the importance of being listened to and being treated with respect. They discussed the difficulty they experienced in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">approaching staff with their problems. The participants explained that they wanted the right balance of caring attention and boundaries; they repeatedly emphasised the importance of wanting to be supported, listened to and understood.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="17" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.68pt; padding-left:1.02pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">A 2012 report by the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> Children’s Rights Director</span><a name="_ftnref9"></a><a href="#_ftn9">[9]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, which r</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">eported on research involving</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> children and young people in care, explained that: “Children may run from a placement or problems they cannot cope with, or to a place where they want to be or to a person they want to be w</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ith.” </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Some young people also discussed running away as a way of instigating a placement move, or of addressing infrequent contact with their family.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">It can be a reaction to a child feeling they are not being listened to</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">When children participating in the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Children’s Rights Director’s research were asked what staff and carers could do to prevent them from running away from care, they responded: </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">‘Sit down and talk to young people – listen to the young people more – find ways of sorting things out for the youn</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">g people.’</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="18" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.68pt; padding-left:1.02pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Listening and understanding the behaviour and complexity of children wh</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">o have had very difficult lives </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">needs professional knowledge and insight built on research</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> and an understanding of child and adolescent development. Measure</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> to develop this are currently missing from the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Government’s </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">proposals. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; text-decoration:underline">The role of commissioners in improving outcomes for children in residential care</span></p><ol start="19" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.68pt; padding-left:1.02pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">78</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">% </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">of children’s homes are now in the private or voluntary sector.</span><a name="_ftnref10"></a><a href="#_ftn10">[10]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> Therefore, it is through the commissioner-provider relationship that local authorities potentially have the most opportunity to influence improvements in the quality of safeguarding and care in children’s homes.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="20" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.68pt; padding-left:1.02pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The OP</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">M report commissioned by the Local G</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">overnment Association</span><a name="_ftnref11"></a><a href="#_ftn11">[11]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">identified ‘widespread questions about the quality assurance and monitoring of placements and homes’ and ‘gaps in understanding about why placement</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">s break down.’</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> Some of those interviewed for the research thought that commissioners a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">re not clear enough about the link between good child outcomes and reduced costs to the local authority and therefore the importance of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">good quality data on outcomes.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> The report also </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">presents evidence that the feedback of children and young people does not</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> always play an important role in quality monitoring: of the children and young people surveyed, ‘30% said no one asked them whether their placement was still right for them once they had been placed and 40% said they had never been asked to help with work</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> to improve children’s homes.’</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="21" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.68pt; padding-left:1.02pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Participants at the NSPCC’s recent sem</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">inar with local providers </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">agreed that c</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ommissioners need to be more discerning about outcomes. They need to recognise the significant needs </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">of</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> children in residential care</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> for instance their mental health needs and the impact of placement breakdowns. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">C</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ommissioning needs to be a partnership between the local authority and the provider to ensure needs are understood and met. There is an important role for the social</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> work team</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> and services such as CAMHS which is too often forgotten, instead of the onus being placed solely on the provider. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Conclusion and k</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">ey r</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">ecommendations</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="22" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.68pt; padding-left:1.02pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Therefore, t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">here</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> are a number of other key features of residential care that should be a central part of the debate to develop </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">a truly ambitious strategy for impro</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ving residential care in the UK:</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 22.7pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">i</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">) Expectations on the quality of care from providers need</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> to be high and t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">here should be greater local authority accountability for the outc</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">omes of children in their care. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Informing the market about need and encouraging new entrants won’t necessarily lead to better quality care, especially if expectations of care, specifications</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> and contract management remain the same. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 22.7pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">ii) The quality of care provided by staff is about much more than qualifications. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Imp</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ortant</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> factors such as leadership and ethos, the size of the care home and the importance of staff consensus and shared working philosophy must not be overlooked and support should be provided to develop these throughout the sector.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 22.7pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">iii</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">) A strong parenting role </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">among care workers is essential</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">This includes</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> activities such as discussing problems and achieving a level of relationship that is more positive than potentially deleterious ones outside of the home.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 22.7pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">iv</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">) </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Commissioning and partnership working are hugely im</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">portant. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Increased</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> efforts must be placed on strategies to encourage placement stability, such as efforts to retain social care staff and provide the continuity of a consistent adult figure.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">P</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">lacement decisions should be based on risk assessments, which sh</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ould include the children and young people already living in a placement and the impact that the ‘new’ child may have on them</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, given levels peer violence</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 22.7pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">v) </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Improvement of support mechanism</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Data and evaluation should be more central to our strategy to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">evalua</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">te what works for care homes. There needs to be more opportunities for sharing good practice between children’s homes given the current lack of a mechanism to do this.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="23" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.68pt; padding-left:1.02pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">To conclude, w</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ithout a wider strategy and support for improvement across the sect</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">or, we fear that these consultation proposals will only have a limited impact on the safety and wellbeing of children and young people in care. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">To ensure that these changes help contribute to change for children and young people there needs to be the artic</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ulation of a wider programme of support and reform for residential care.  </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">September 2013</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div><hr style="width:33%; height:1px; text-align:left" /><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn1"></a><a href="#_ftnref1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:7pt"> Hannon. C, Wood. C and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:7pt">Bazalgette</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:7pt">. L (2010) ‘In Loco Parentis’, Demos </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn2"></a><a href="#_ftnref2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:7pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:7pt">Children’s Homes in England Data Pack, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:7pt">DfE</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:7pt"> (September 2013)</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 70.9pt 0pt 0pt; text-align:justify"><a name="_ftn3"></a><a href="#_ftnref3">[3]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:7pt"> Meltzer, H., </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:7pt">Gatward</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:7pt">, R., Corbin, T., Goodman, R., &amp; Ford, T. (2003)</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn4"></a><a href="#_ftnref4">[4]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:7pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:7pt">Children’s Homes in England Data Pack, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:7pt">DfE</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:7pt"> (September 2013)</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn5"></a><a href="#_ftnref5">[5]</a><sp